Kinds, edge types, and headers are just strings. The vocabulary
is open by design. There is no validation, no enum, no closed list.

An agent or human can write 'kind celebration' or 'kind debt' and
it just works. 'mycelium.sh kinds' shows what's in use — that's the
only registry, and it's descriptive not prescriptive.

This matters because culture evolves. If we hardcode kinds, changing
our minds requires a migration. If kinds are strings, changing our
minds requires writing a new note.

Story: we started with 6 kinds (decision, context, summary, warning,
constraint, observation). During dogfooding we realized we needed
'value' for cultural principles that aren't constraints. We just
used it — no spec change, no migration, no version bump. The tool
already supported it because it never restricted it.
